  "Idea": "We propose a novel end-to-end unsupervised framework that jointly optimizes syntactic structure induction and visual-semantic alignment through mutual reinforcement between modality-invariant representation learning and hierarchical linguistic structure discovery. The key insight is that visual scenes provide implicit grounding signals that can guide the discovery of syntactically plausible sentence decompositions, while syntactic structures—when modeled as latent tree variables—can act as structural priors that regularize and refine cross-modal attention mechanisms. Our model introduces two co-adaptive components: (1) a Latent Syntactic Induction Module (LSIM), which learns to parse sentences into hierarchical phrase structures using differentiable tree approximations without gold syntax annotations, and (2) a Visual-Syntactic Alignment Encoder (VSAE), which leverages image regions and object relationships to supervise the plausibility of induced parses via cross-modal consistency losses. These components interact through a dual-objective optimization scheme: maximizing visual-semantic similarity under structurally grounded attention, while simultaneously refining syntactic hypotheses based on cross-modal agreement scores. To enable efficient learning, we employ a neural expectation-maximization-like procedure where E-step samples plausible latent syntactic trees conditioned on current visual-semantic alignments, and M-step updates both the alignment model and syntax generator to maximize expected joint likelihood. Crucially, no parallel syntactic trees or aligned captions are required; instead, the system bootstraps from raw image-text pairs by leveraging distributional statistics and geometric correspondences (e.g., spatial layout of objects matching noun phrase modifiers). This enables the emergence of interpretable, compositionally faithful language structures that are tightly coupled with visual semantics. The framework has broad implications for zero-shot multimodal understanding, unsupervised grammar induction, and robust cross-modal retrieval in low-resource settings. By unifying structure-aware representation learning and multimodal alignment under a single objective, our method advances the frontier of unsupervised foundation models capable of discovering both meaning and form autonomously.",
