  "Experiment": "The implementation consists of four stages: (1) \u003cb\u003eData Preparation\u003c/b\u003e: Use COCO and Conceptual Captions datasets with raw image-caption pairs. Extract visual features using a pre-trained Faster R-CNN with ResNet-101 backbone, including bounding boxes, class logits, and spatial coordinates. Tokenize text using BERT tokenizer. No manual syntactic annotation is used. (2) \u003cb\u003eModel Architecture\u003c/b\u003e: Design a dual-path encoder. The \u003ci\u003eSyntactic Induction Path\u003c/i\u003e uses a Transformer with Gumbel-Tree Sampling layers to generate stochastic constituency parses, outputting a distribution over binary tree structures. The \u003ci\u003eVisual Reasoning Path\u003c/i\u003e implements a differentiable NMN with learnable operators (find[object], relate[spatial], describe[attribute]) that take parsed phrases as control signals. Outputs are routed through a stack-augmented memory module that maintains state across syntactic levels. A multimodal fusion head computes contrastive alignment scores between final sentence representation and global image features. (3) \u003cb\u003eTraining Procedure\u003c/b\u003e: Train via variational EM. In E-step, sample K parse trees per sentence using Gumbel-Softmax relaxation. For each sample, execute the NMN to produce a grounded representation. In M-step, compute a joint loss combining contrastive alignment (InfoNCE), parse likelihood (variational lower bound), and syntax-aware reconstruction (masking entire phrases and predicting words from visual context). Update all components via reparameterized gradients. Use curriculum learning: start with short captions, gradually increase length. (4) \u003cb\u003eEvaluation\u003c/b\u003e: Evaluate on (a) Unsupervised Parsing: F1 score (against WSJ-PTB) using EVALB; (b) Visual-Semantic Retrieval: R@1, R@5 on COCO; (c) Compositional Generalization: test on rare adjective-noun combinations not seen in training; (d) Interpretability: visualize execution traces linking noun phrases to detected objects and relational reasoning steps. Baselines include SCAN, UNIALIGN, and TreeLSTM-based models. We expect NSR to achieve superior performance in all metrics, especially in compositional splits, demonstrating the benefit of syntax as an active computational mechanism rather than a passive constraint.",
